snippet.title: Samsung Galaxy Mega hits the United States
snippet.description: Outfitted with a 6.3-inch screen, the smartphone will be carried by AT&T, Sprint, and U.S. Cellular. AT&T will get things rolling with the Mega this Friday.

snippet.title: YouTube app comes to the Wii in the United States
snippet.description: With its arrival on the Wii, YouTube is now available on 400 million devices, Google says.

snippet.title: Don't loan your iPhone to people in these states
snippet.description: SquareTrade releases data showing that Washington isn't just the nation's capital, it's also the scariest place in the country to be an iPhone.

snippet.title: VC Tim Draper: Maybe US will end up with 60 states
snippet.description: High-profile venture capitalist says his plan to split California into six different states could get other states thinking the same thing.

snippet.title: United Airlines site loophole reoffers uber cheap fares
snippet.description: A Web site malfunction lets users trick the airline into offering them tickets with frequent-flyer miles they don't have.

snippet.title: Error on United Airlines Web site results in free fares
snippet.description: For a brief period earlier today, travelers shopping for fares on United.com were able to book tickets for a $0 base fare.

snippet.title: Xperia Play misses United States in initial release
snippet.description: The era of the PlayStation Phone begins as Sony Ericsson releases the handset to nearly one dozen markets. The United States, however, will have to wait.

snippet.title: YouTube Trends Map shows most popular videos across U.S.
snippet.description: A new tool tracks the most watched YouTube videos in real time. Videos can be filtered via highest number of views or shares, as well as by gender and age of viewers.

snippet.title: Report: United States is world's top spammer
snippet.description: New report from security vendor Sophos finds the U.S. accounts for almost 19 percent of all spam sent through the world, or one in five of all junk e-mails.

snippet.title: Google Map Maker arrives in U.K.
snippet.description: The United Kingdom's denizens now can add detail such as paths and businesses to Google's online maps service. But remember: it's free labor for Google.
